8 Admin commands
****************

All commands require ‘root’ or ‘casuser’.  Installed under
‘/usr/lib/casmgr/bin/’ and ‘/usr/sbin/’.

8.1 casmgr-postgres-container
=============================

Manage Docker container ‘casmgr-postgres’.

‘pull’
     Download image from ‘/usr/share/casmgr/docker-image’.
‘recreate’
     Remove existing container and create a new one with host bind
     mounts.  Uses ‘POSTGRES_SUPERUSER_PASSWORD’ and ‘POSTGRES_DB’ from
     secrets.  Publishes PostgreSQL on ‘127.0.0.1:5432’ (port from
     config).
‘start’
     Start container; runs ‘recreate’ if missing.
‘stop’
     Stop container.
‘remove’
     Stop and remove container (image retained).
‘status’
     Print container name, state, and image.

     sudo casmgr-postgres-container pull
     sudo casmgr-postgres-container recreate
     sudo casmgr-postgres-container status

8.2 casmgr-pg-init
==================

Bootstrap PostgreSQL after the container is running:

   • Apply superuser password from secrets.
   • Create application role and database from ‘config.json’ driver
     settings.
   • Grant privileges on database and ‘public’ schema.

   Option ‘--fix-existing-db-owner’ runs ‘ALTER DATABASE ... OWNER’ when
the database already exists.

     sudo systemctl start casmgr-postgres
     sudo casmgr-pg-init
     sudo casmgr-pg-init --fix-existing-db-owner

8.3 casmgr-pg-set-password
==========================

Apply passwords from ‘/var/casmgr/secrets/.env’ to the running cluster.

   Default: updates superuser and application role (‘ALTER ROLE’).
Option ‘--superuser-only’ skips the application role.

   When rotating the superuser password, set
‘POSTGRES_SUPERUSER_CONNECT_PASSWORD’ to the current cluster password
for that run.

     sudo casmgr-pg-set-password
     sudo casmgr-pg-set-password --superuser-only

8.4 casmgr
==========

Daemon manager CLI (‘/usr/bin/casmgr’).  Uses the package venv under
‘/usr/lib/casmgr-server’.

‘--config PATH’
     Config file (default ‘/etc/casmgr/config.json’ via
     ‘CASMGR_CONFIG’).
‘start’, ‘stop’, ‘restart’, ‘status’
     Manage MCP daemon outside systemd or inspect process state.
‘sessions’, ‘locks’
     List active client sessions and file locks.

   Production service management should use systemd; use ‘casmgr’ for
debugging.

     sudo casmgr --config /etc/casmgr/config.json status
     sudo casmgr --config /etc/casmgr/config.json restart

8.5 casmgr_ensure_instance_uuid
===============================

Python helper at
‘/usr/lib/casmgr-server/scripts/casmgr_ensure_instance_uuid.py’.
Ensures ‘registration.instance_uuid’ is a valid UUID4.  Invoked from
package ‘postinst’.

     sudo /usr/lib/casmgr-server/.venv/bin/python \
       /usr/lib/casmgr-server/scripts/casmgr_ensure_instance_uuid.py \
       --config /etc/casmgr/config.json
     sudo .../casmgr_ensure_instance_uuid.py --dry-run


